## Core rule (the only hard constraint)

Do not change the public contract other code relies on: keep the same function/method
names, parameters, and return types for anything that could be called from outside the
lines you're fixing. Do not modify test files, CI config, or build/setup scripts. Do not
change behavior for inputs unrelated to the finding below.

Everything else is your judgment call — fix the issue properly.

## You are encouraged to

- Add new imports if the fix genuinely needs them (a safer library call, a stdlib helper,
  a proper exception type, etc.).
- Add helper logic, validation, or error handling near the fix site if that's what a
  correct fix requires.
- Touch more than just the exact flagged line(s) when the vulnerability or bug requires
  restructuring a block (e.g. wrapping in a parameterized query, adding a missing bounds
  check, closing a resource properly).
- Rename or adjust *private/local* variables and internal helpers introduced by your fix.

## Avoid

- Rewriting or refactoring code that has nothing to do with the finding.
- Changing the signature of a function/method that other files may call.
- "Fixing" by deleting functionality instead of correcting it.

## When a fix isn't possible

Only set `"changed": false` if a correct fix is genuinely impossible without breaking the
public contract above (e.g. the vulnerability is architectural and needs a signature
change). Do not use `"changed": false` just because the fix touches more than one line —
a real, complete fix is the goal.

